{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1778080777,"nonce":"FdIj5KSioKdzir+WJHRBwlaUAeU=","title":"Damping calibration retraining: k in {0.1, 1, 10} as controlled diagnostic","message":"Train rlrmp models at varying plant damping (k=0.1 matches C\u0026S, k=1 intermediate, k=10 current rlrmp). All else equal — same architecture, same training method, same SISU schedule.\n\n**Purpose:**\nSeparates parameter-regime contribution from objective-form contribution to the velocity-signature gap. Production Riccati predicts ~0%% signature on C\u0026S regime (k=0.1) and +5–13%% on rlrmp regime (k=10). Empirical training should track this *if objective form alone is the issue*. Deviations from the prediction reveal regime-specific effects we missed.\n\n**Test matrix:**\n- 3 damping values × current best training method (standard or APT) × 3 seeds.\n- Compute Δv vs LQR baseline at each damping.\n\n**Pre-registered falsification:**\n- If empirical Δv at k=10 reaches +5–13%% under any (a)-flavor training method, objective form is *not* the bottleneck — back to the drawing board.\n- If empirical Δv at k=0.1 is non-zero, there is a parameter-regime effect beyond what the Riccati predicts.\n\nReferences: synthesis_review §10.2 (calibration), §11 step 5. Umbrella: b557d4e. Depends on 5a44bd3 (Riccati for prediction targets).","files":null}]}